    <section class="chemistry-matters" id="sect-00004">
    <title><emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-Lactam Antibiotics</title>
    <para id="para-00007">You should never underestimate the value of hard work and logical thinking, but it’s also true that blind luck often plays a role in most real scientific breakthroughs. What has been called “the supreme example of luck in all scientific history” occurred in the late summer of 1928, when the Scottish bacteriologist Alexander Fleming went on vacation, leaving in his lab a culture plate recently inoculated with the bacterium <emphasis effect="italics">Staphylococcus aureus</emphasis>.</para>
    <figure class="scaled-down-30" id="fig-00002">
    <media alt="Image of penicillium growing in a dish of vinegar.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_98_Penicilli.jpg"/>
    </media>
    <caption>Penicillium mold growing in a petri dish. (credit: “Penicillium notatum on beetroot vinegar. June 1965” by Dr Mary Gillham Archive Project/Flickr, CC BY 2.0)</caption>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00008">While Fleming was away, an extraordinary chain of events occurred. First, a nine-day cold spell lowered the laboratory temperature to a point where the <emphasis effect="italics">Staphylococcus</emphasis> in the culture plate could not grow. During this time, spores from a colony of the mold <emphasis effect="italics">Penicillium notatum,</emphasis> being grown in a lab on the floor below, wafted up into Fleming’s lab and landed in the culture plate. The temperature then rose, and both <emphasis effect="italics">Staphylococcus</emphasis> and <emphasis effect="italics">Penicillium</emphasis> began to grow. On returning from vacation, Fleming discarded the plate into a tray of antiseptic, intending to sterilize it. Evidently, though, the plate did not sink deeply enough into the antiseptic, because when Fleming happened to glance at it a few days later, what he saw changed the course of history. He noticed that the growing <emphasis effect="italics">Penicillium</emphasis> mold appeared to dissolve the colonies of staphylococci.</para>
    <para id="para-00009">Fleming realized that the <emphasis effect="italics">Penicillium</emphasis> mold must be producing a chemical that killed the <emphasis effect="italics">Staphylococcus</emphasis> bacteria, and he spent several years trying to isolate the substance. Finally, in 1939, the Australian pathologist Howard Florey and the German refugee Ernst Chain managed to isolate the active substance, called <emphasis effect="italics">penicillin.</emphasis> The dramatic ability of penicillin to cure infections in mice was soon demonstrated, and successful tests in humans followed shortly thereafter. By 1943, penicillin was being produced on a large scale for military use in World War II, and by 1944 it was being used on civilians. Fleming, Florey, and Chain shared the 1945 Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine.</para>
    <para id="para-00010">Now called benzylpenicillin, or penicillin G, the substance first discovered by Fleming is but one member of a large class of so-called <emphasis effect="bold"><emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-lactam antibiotics</emphasis>, compounds with a four-membered lactam (cyclic amide) ring. The four-membered lactam ring is fused to a five-membered, sulfur-containing ring, and the carbon atom next to the lactam carbonyl group is bonded to an acylamino substituent, RCONH–. This acylamino side chain can be varied in the laboratory to provide many hundreds of penicillin analogs with different biological activity profiles. Ampicillin, for instance, has an <emphasis effect="italics">α</emphasis>-aminophenylacetamido substituent [PhCH(NH<sub>2</sub>)CONH–].</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00003">
    <media alt="An illustration shows the structure of Benzylpenicillin (penicillin G). It shows a benzene bonded to a methylene group bonded to a carbonyl group that is bonded to a nitrogen monohydride. The CO-NH bond is labeled ‘Acylamino substituent.’ The structure from benzene to nitrogen is highlighted in green. The nitrogen is wedge bonded to a cyclobutane ring highlighted in pink (labeled ‘beta-lactam ring) that shows a nitrogen and is double bonded to a pink oxygen and dash bonded to two hydrogen atoms. The cyclobutane is fused to a cyclopentane that shows a sulfur. The cyclopentane is single bonded to two methyl groups and dash bonded to a carboxylate ion bonded to sodium cation.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_10_003.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00011">Closely related to the penicillins are the <emphasis effect="italics">cephalosporins</emphasis>, a group of <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-lactam antibiotics that contain an unsaturated, six-membered, sulfur-containing ring. Cephalexin, marketed under the trade name Keflex, is an example. Cephalosporins generally have much greater antibacterial activity than penicillins, particularly against resistant strains of bacteria.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00004">
    <media alt="An illustration shows the structure of Cephalexin (a cephalosporin). It shows a benzene bonded to a methine group bonded to an amino group and carbonyl group that is bonded to a nitrogen monohydride. The nitrogen is wedge bonded to a cyclobutane ring that shows a nitrogen and is double bonded to an oxygen and dash bonded to two hydrogen atoms. The cyclobutane is fused to a cyclohexene that shows a sulfur. The cyclohexane is single bonded to a methyl group and carboxylic acid.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_10_004.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    <para id="para-00012">The biological activity of penicillins and cephalosporins is due to the presence of the strained <emphasis effect="italics">β</emphasis>-lactam ring, which reacts with and deactivates the transpeptidase enzyme needed to synthesize and repair bacterial cell walls. With the wall either incomplete or weakened, the bacterial cell ruptures and dies.</para>
    <figure class="unnumbered scaled-down" id="fig-00005">
    <media alt="An illustration shows a reaction in which Penicillin (beta -lactam) reacts with Transpeptidase (active enzyme) to yield an intermediate that after several steps yields an inactive enzyme. The structure of penicillin shows an R bonded to a carbonyl group that is bonded to a nitrogen monohydride. The nitrogen is wedge bonded to a cyclobutane ring that shows a blue nitrogen and is double bonded to a pink oxygen and dash bonded to two hydrogen atoms. The cyclobutane is fused to a cyclopentane that shows a sulfur. The cyclopentane is single bonded to two methyl groups and dash bonded to a carboxyl group. Transpeptidase shows an enzyme bonded to blue hydroxyl group that shows four electrons. An arrow from the electrons points to the double bond between the cyclobutane and pink oxygen. An arrow from the double bond points to the pink oxygen. The intermediate is similar to the reactant but the pink oxygen is single bonded and shows a negative charge and six electrons. The carbon bonded to the pink oxygen is also bonded to a blue oxygen that is bonded to Enzyme. An arrow from the electrons of pink oxygen points to the bond between the cyclobutane and pink oxygen. An arrow from the C-blue N bond points to H of H-A. An arrow from the H-A bond points to A. The inactive enzyme shows an R bonded to a carbonyl group that is bonded to a nitrogen monohydride. The nitrogen is wedge bonded to an open cyclobutane ring that shows a blue nitrogen monohydride and is double bonded to a pink oxygen and dash bonded to two hydrogen atoms. The pink oxygen is bonded to a blue oxygen that is bonded to Enzyme. The cyclobutane is fused to a cyclopentane that shows a sulfur. The cyclopentane is single bonded to two methyl groups and dash bonded to a carboxyl group.">
    <image mime-type="image/jpeg" src="../../media/OChem_21_10_005.jpg"/>
    </media>
    </figure>
    </section>
